{{Infobox person | name = Kâtip Çelebi | image = Map of the Indian Ocean and the China Sea was engraved in 1728 by Ibrahim Müteferrika.jpg | alt = | caption = This map of the [[Indian Ocean]] and the [[Chinese Sea]] was engraved in 1728 by the Hungarian-born Ottoman cartographer and publisher [[Ibrahim Muteferrika|Ibrahim Müteferrika]]; it is one of a series that illustrated Katip Çelebi's ''Universal Geography'', the first printed book of maps and drawings to appear in the Islamic world. | birth_name = Mustafa bin Abdullah<ref>{{cite book|author1=Mathias Bernath|author2=Felix von Schroeder|title=Biographisches Lexikon zur Geschichte Südosteuropas|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=I_sb13u8AyoC&pg=PA270|year=1979|publisher=Oldenbourg Verlag|isbn=978-3-486-48991-0|page=270|quote=Mustafa bin 'Abdullah (= Mustafa Sohn des Abdullah, gewöhnlich Katib oder Haci Halife genannt)}}</ref> | birth_date = February 1609 | birth_place = [[Constantinople]], Ottoman Empire (now Turkey) | death_date = 26 September 1657<!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) --> | death_place = Constantinople, Ottoman Empire | nationality = | other_names = Haji Kalfa, Hacı Halife | occupation = Historian, geographer | years_active = | known_for = | notable_works = }}
'''Kâtip Çelebi''' ({{lang-ota|كاتب چلبى|Kātib Çelebi}} "Gentleman Scribe"), the pen name of '''Mustafa bin Abdullah''' (1609–1657), also later known as '''Haji Khalifa''' ({{lang-tr|Hacı Halife}}) or '''Kalfa''',<ref>Piterberg (2003), p. 46</ref><ref>Shefer-Mossensohn (2015), pp. 64-65</ref> was an [[Ottoman Empire|Ottoman]] scholar. A historian and geographer, he is regarded as one of the most productive authors of non-religious, scientific literature in the 17th-century Ottoman Empire.<ref>Piterberg (2003), p. 46</ref>
==Life== [[File:Tile with Calligraphy.JPG|thumb|The main motif is a [[calligraphic]] pattern formed from the names of God, the prophet [[Muhammad]] and the first four caliphs, [[Abu Bakr]], ‘[[Umar]], [[Uthman ibn Affan|‘Uthman]] and ‘[[Ali]] written in [[Arabic]]. The combination indicates an allegiance to [[Sunni Islam]]. Ceramic tile, Constantinople, cira 1727, Islamic Middle East Gallery]]
Kâtip Çelebi was born as Mustafa, the son of an Abdullah, in Constantinople ([[Istanbul]]).<ref>Piterberg (2003), p. 46</ref> He began his studies at the age of five or six, and became an apprentice in the Ottoman financial bureaucracy at the age of fourteen.<ref>Shefer-Mossensohn (2015), pp. 65</ref> As the accountant of the commissariat department of the [[Ottoman army]] in [[Anatolia]], he accompanied the Ottoman army in the suppression of the rebellion of [[Abaza Mehmed Pasha]] in 1624,<ref>Piterberg (2003), p. 47</ref> as well as during the [[Ottoman–Safavid War (1623–39)|Ottoman-Safavid War of 1629-1639]], particularly in the campaigns at [[Baghdad]] in 1625, and at the siege of [[Erzurum]]. He returned to Constantinople in 1628. In the following year he was again in Baghdad and [[Hamadan]], and in 1633-34 at [[Aleppo]], whence he made the [[pilgrimage to Mecca]] (hence his title ''Hajji''). The following year he was in [[Erivan]] and then returned to Constantinople. Here he obtained a post in the head office of the commissariat department, which afforded him time for study. An inheritance which he received in 1645 enabled him to live comfortably in the Ottoman capital of Constantinople and dedicate his time to scholarship.<ref>Piterberg (2003), p. 47</ref> Kâtip Çelebi died untimely in 1657.<ref>Piterberg (2003), p. 47</ref>
==Works== Many of his works were composed between 1648 and his death in 1657.<ref>Piterberg (2003), p. 47</ref> Among his best-known works is the ''Kashf al-ẓunūn ‘an asāmī al-kutub wa-al-funūn'', ({{lang|ar|كشف الظنون عن أسامي الكتب والفنون}}) ("The Removal of Doubt from the Names of Books and the Arts"), a [[bibliography|bibliographic]] encyclopaedia, written in [[Arabic language|Arabic]], which lists more than 14,500 books in [[alphabetic order]].<ref name="Bekir">Bekir Karliga, [http://www.muslimheritage.com/topics/default.cfm?articleID=1137 "The Horizon of Katip Celebi's Thought"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121009175059/http://www.muslimheritage.com/topics/default.cfm?articleID=1137 |date=2012-10-09 }} in the MuslimHeritage.com</ref><ref>Ruveyda Ozturk, Salim Ayduz, [http://muslimheritage.com/topics/default.cfm?ArticleID=1067 "A Jewel of Ottoman Naval History: The Book of Kâtip Çelebi on Naval Campaigns"] in the MuslimHeritage.com</ref><ref>[http://muslimheritage.com/topics/default.cfm?ArticleID=658 "Ottoman Maritime Arsenals And Shipbuilding Technology In The 16th And 17th Centuries"] in the MuslimHeritage.com</ref>
One of his shorter and more accessible works is ''Mīzānü'l-ḥaḳḳ fī iḫtiyāri'l-aḥaḳḳ'' ({{lang|ar|ميزان الحق في اختيار الأحق}}) ("The balance of truth in the choice of the truest"), a collection of short essays on topics in Islamic law, ethics, and theology, in which he takes a relatively liberal and tolerant view—often critical of narrow-minded Islamic religious authorities. This book serves as a source on Ottoman social developments in the 16th and 17th centuries, such as the introduction of [[coffee]] and [[tobacco]]. While he did not concur with the outlawing of coffee and tobacco, he found tobacco smoke personally distasteful, writing of the "noxious effects of the corruption of the aerial essence." An English translation by [[Geoffrey Lewis (Turkish scholar)|G. L. Lewis]] of the ''Mīzān al-ḥaqq'' has been published with annotations under the title ''The Balance of Truth''.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Balance of Truth|year=1957|location=London|author=Kâtip Çelebi}} Translated with an introduction and notes by G. L. Lewis.</ref>
== Legacy == There is a university named after him, İzmir Kâtip Çelebi University in [[İzmir]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ikc.edu.tr/|access-date=21 August 2015|title= İzmir Kâtip Çelebi Üniversitesi}}</ref> Turkey and the UK have an ongoing science and innovation exchange program called the Newton-Katip Çelebi Fund.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.britishcouncil.org.tr/en/programmes/education/newton-katip-celebi-fund|access-date=21 August 2015|title=Newton-Katip Çelebi Fund - British Council}}</ref>
