{{Infobox protected area | name = Lemmenjoki National Park | iucn_category = Ib | iucn_ref = <!-- images --> | photo = File:Lemmenjoki Autumn.JPG | photo_caption = Autumn colours at River Lemmenjoki at Lemmenjoki National Park in Finland <!-- map --> | map = | map_image = Lemmenjokinationalpark.png | map_size = | map_caption = Lemmenjoki and Øvre Anarjohka national parks on map. Lemmenjoki is the larger green area. | relief = <!-- location --> | location = [[Lapland (Finland)|Lapland]], Finland | nearest_city = | nearest_town = | coordinates = {{coord|68|30|N|025|30|E|display=inline,title}} | coords_ref = <!-- stats --> | length = | length_mi = | length_km = | width = | width_mi = | width_km = | area_km2 = 2850 | area_ref = | elevation = | elevation_avg = | elevation_min = | elevation_max = | dimensions = | designation = <!-- dates & info --> | authorized = | created = | designated = | established = 1956 | named_for = | visitation_num = 10000 | visitation_year = 2009<ref>{{cite web|url= http://www.metsa.fi/sivustot/metsa/fi/Eraasiatjaretkeily/Asiakastieto/Kayntimaarat/Kansallispuistoittain/Sivut/kayntimaaratkansallispuistoittain2009.aspx|title= Käyntimäärät kansallispuistoittain 2009|accessdate= September 29, 2010|language= Finnish|publisher=[[Metsähallitus]]}}</ref> | visitation_ref = | governing_body = Metsähallitus | administrator = | operator = | owner = <!-- website, embedded --> | website = {{URL|http://www.nationalparks.fi/lemmenjokinp}} | embedded = }}
'''Lemmenjoki National Park''' ({{lang-fi|Lemmenjoen kansallispuisto}}, {{lang-se|Leammi álbmotmeahcci}}) is situated in area of municipalities of [[Inari, Finland|Inari]] and [[Kittilä]], [[Lapland (Finland)|Lapland]], in Northern [[Finland]]. It was founded in 1956 and has since been expanded twice. Its total area is {{convert|2850|km2|sqmi|0}}, making it the biggest national park of Finland and one of the largest in [[Europe]].
The park is named after the [[Lemmenjoki River]], an {{convert|80|km|-1}} long river running through it.
The park is partly bordered by the [[Øvre Anarjóhka National Park]] in [[Norway]].
Around 100 people can be seen digging gold in the area in the summer on 40 claims. Most of the people in the park &ndash; around 10,000 people per year &ndash; are backpackers, though. There are about {{convert|60|km|-1}} marked paths in the [[national park]], and even some bridges and boats are put up for travelers. There are more than ten free [[wilderness hut]]s in the park and three chargeable, bookable ones.
The gold-digging area contains two small [[airfield]]s, Martiniiskonpalo<ref>{{cite web |url=https://lentopaikat.fi/martiniiskonpalo-efmp/ |title=Martiniiskonpalo (EFMP) |author=<!--Not stated--> |date=August 20, 2014 |website=lentopaikat.fi |publisher=Finnish Aeronautical Association |access-date=January 7, 2018 |language=Finnish}}</ref> ({{convert|467|m|abbr=on|disp=or}}) and Keurulainen (about {{convert|500|m|-2|abbr=on|disp=or}}). They can be used for landing or taking off with small propeller planes.
