{{Use Australian English|date=May 2014}} {{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}} {{Infobox waterfall | name = Russell Falls | photo = Russell Falls 2.jpg | photo_width = 280px | photo_caption = Lower curtain of Russell Falls | map = Tasmania | relief = yes | map_width = 250px | coordinates = {{coord|42|40|12|S|146|42|36|E|region:AU-TAS_type:waterbody_scale:50000|format=dms|display=inline,title}} | coords_ref = <ref name=ga1>{{Gazetteer of Australia|name=Russell Falls (TAS)|feature=TAS00716}}</ref> | location = [[Central Highlands (Tasmania)|Central Highlands]], [[Tasmania]], [[Australia]] | type = [[Waterfall#Types|Tiered{{endash}}cascade]] | elevation = {{convert|295|m}}<ref name=bonzle>{{cite web|url=http://www.bonzle.com/c/a?a=p&p=253405&cmd=sp|title=Map of Russell Falls, TAS|work=Bonzle Digital Atlas of Australia|date=|accessdate=31 May 2014}}</ref> | height = {{convert|34|-|58|m}}<ref name=bonzle/> | height_longest = | number_drops = 2 | width = | average_width = | watercourse = Russell Falls Creek | average_flow = | world_rank = }}
The '''Russell Falls''', a [[Waterfall#Types|tiered{{endash}}cascade waterfall]] on the Russell Falls Creek, is located in the [[Central Highlands (Tasmania)|Central Highlands]] region of [[Tasmania]], [[Australia]].
==Location and features== The Russell Falls are situated on the eastern boundary of [[Mount Field National Park]], {{convert|100|m|ft}} downstream of the [[Horseshoe Falls (Tasmania)|Horseshoe Falls]], approximately {{convert|70|km}} northwest of [[Hobart]] via the [[Brooker Highway|Brooker]] and [[Lyell Highway|Lyell]] highways. Accessible by a paved walking track, the falls are a popular [[tourism|tourist]] attraction. The waterfall descends over horizontal marine [[Permian]] [[siltstone]] benches, while the vertical faces of the falls are composed of resistant [[sandstone]] layers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tastrails.com/russell-falls-and-horseshoe-falls/|title=Russell Falls and Horseshoe Falls|work=TasTrails|date=2014|accessdate=31 May 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.parks.tas.gov.au/index.aspx?base=3589|title=Mt Field National Park|work=Parks & Wildlife Service|publisher=[[Government of Tasmania]]|date=19 April 2012|accessdate=31 May 2014}}</ref><ref name=Highlights>{{cite web |title=Mt Field National Park: Highlights|url=http://www.parks.tas.gov.au/index.aspx?base=3601|date=19 March 2009|work=Parks & Wildlife Service|publisher=[[Government of Tasmania]]|accessdate=31 May 2014}}</ref>
They were first named the Brownings Falls after the original discoverer, ''circa''1856, but were known as the Russell Falls after 1884, by which time they were already a popular tourist attraction.<ref name=Highlights /> The Falls Reserve was established in 1885 and in 1899 the Russell Falls were selected as one of eight images to be used on a [[Postage stamps and postal history of Tasmania|set of pictorial postage stamps]], aimed at promoting the then colony's growing tourist industry.
==Gallery== <gallery> Russell Falls Mt Field National Park.jpg|Lower curtain of Russell Falls with upper tiers visible at top of image Upper Tier Of Russell Falls 4787.jpg|The upper tier of Russell Falls </gallery>
