{{Infobox book <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Novels or Wikipedia:WikiProject_Books --> |name=''The Face of Appalachia: Portraits from the Mountain Farm'' |title_orig= |image=The Face of Appalachia.jpg |caption=First edition cover |author=[[Timothy Lee Barnwell]] |cover_artist= |country=United States |language=English |series= |pages=158 (First Edition) |genre=[[Photography]] |published=2003 [[W.W. Norton]] |ISBN=0-393-05787-9 }}
'''''The Face of Appalachia: Portraits from the Mountain Farm''''' is a 2003 hardcover book by photographer and author [[Timothy Lee Barnwell]]. It is a mixture of photography and [[oral history]] text about the culture of [[Appalachia]]. It was first published on December 17, 2003 [[W.W. Norton]] and includes over 100 black and white photographs as well as interviews with the Appalachia inhabitants depicted.<ref>{{cite web|title=Still lifes of Appalachia: Asheville photographer Tim Barnwell spends his life capturing artistic images of disappearing rural ways|url=http://www.smliv.com/features/1270-still-lifes-of-appalachia-asheville-photographer-tim-barnwell-spends-his-life-capturing-artistic-images-of-disappearing-rural-ways.html|publisher=Smoky Mountain Living|accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref>
==Synopsis== The book presents photos and interviews taken over a 25-year period. Photographs cover elements of Appalachia life such as farming, hunting, community and religious activities. Material is compiled into eight chapters, each of which focuses on specific things associated with the community and with Appalachian life.
==Reception== Critical reception for ''The Face of Appalachia'' has been positive.<ref>{{cite news|last=Walpole|first=Peter|title=The Face of Appalachia: Portraits from the Mountain Farm (review)|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-662696231.html|accessdate=26 January 2014|newspaper=The Virginia Quarterly Review|date=July 1, 2004}}</ref> ''Black and White Magazine'' and ''[[The New York Times]]'' both gave positive reviews of the book,<ref>{{cite web|title=Tim Barnwell (review)|url=http://www.bandwmag.com/back-issues/bw-no-12|publisher=Black and White Magazine|accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref> with ''The New York Times'' noting that the work was "a notable work of anthropology."<ref>{{cite web|last=MacNeille|first=Suzanne|title=BOOKS IN BRIEF: NONFICTION; An Eye on Appalachia|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/02/29/books/books-in-brief-nonfiction-an-eye-on-appalachia.html|publisher=NYT|accessdate=26 January 2014}}</ref>
